==Old English==
===Etymology===
(Closely related to [[leode|lēode]] and [[leodan|lēodan]].)  From Germanic ''*leudi-'', from Indo-European ''*leudh-'' ‘grow, come up’.  Cognates include Old High German [[liut]], Old Norse ''ljōðr''; and, outside the Germanic languages, Lithuanian [[liaudis|liáudis]] ‘common people’, Old Church Slavonic ''l’udъ'' (Russian [[люд]]).

